class=\"linenumber\">7\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003Cbr id=\"al8-diplomatic\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">8\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003Cbr id=\"al9-diplomatic\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">9\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003Cbr id=\"al10-diplomatic\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">10\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003Cbr id=\"al11-diplomatic\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">11\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003Cbr id=\"al12-diplomatic\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">12\u003C/span>QV[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\u003C/div>\u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"facsimile-images\">\u003Ch2>Facsimile Images\u003C/h2>\u003Ca href=\"ISic000492_tiled.tif\">\u003Cimg title=\"Photo courtesy of M. Silvestrini\" src=\"ISic000492_tiled-thumb.tif\">\u003C/a>\u003Ca href=\"ISic000492.jpg\">\u003Cimg title=\"Photo courtesy of M. Silvestrini\" src=\"ISic000492-thumb.jpg\">\u003C/a>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"apparatus\">\u003Ch4>Apparatus criticus\u003C/h4>\u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003Cspan>\u003Cspan>Text of CIL, compared against photograph\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"translation\">\u003Ch2> translation\u003C/h2>\u003Cp class=\"translation-author\">  \u003C/p>\u003Cp>  \u003C/p>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"commentary\">\u003Ch2>commentary\u003C/h2>  \u003Cp>The upper part of the stone is currently located in the courtyard of the Palazzo Vescovile in Mazara del Vallo; there is no trace of the lower part of the stone, previously recorded in CIL and by earlier authors. The text almost certainly honours the same individual as \u003Ca href=\"http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic003460\" target=\"_blank\">ISic003460\u003C/a>, found in Marsala in 2010. Whether the stone was transferred after antiquity from Marsala, as has often been suggested, or whether Mazara was a subordinate community of Lilybaeum in the Roman period, remains uncertain.\u003C/p>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"bibliography\">\u003Ch2>bibliography\u003C/h2>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> Gualtherus 1624 [1625] 118 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001931\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001931\u003C/a>  \u003C/li>\u003Cli> Mommsen 1883 \u003Ca href=\"http://arachne.uni-koeln.de/books/CILv10pII1883\" target=\"_blank\">7212\u003C/a>  \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000589\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000589\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Manganaro 1988 53, 76 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001427\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001427\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Silvestrini 2020 294, 296-298 with figs. 4-5 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002609\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002609\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"handnote\"> Line 1    Interlineation line 1 to 2    \u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"license\"> Licensed under a Creative Commons-Attribution 4.0 licence.  \u003C/div>",[212,215,218,221,224,227,230,233],{"id":213,"html":214},"editions","\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Text encoding: Jonathan Prag\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-interpretive\" lang=\"la\">  \u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\">  \u003Ca id=\"al1-interpretive\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>M(arco) Rubellino \u003Cbr id=\"al2-interpretive\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">2\u003C/span>P(ubli) f(ilio) Publ(io) Cestiano Cras-\u003Cbr id=\"al3-interpretive\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">3\u003C/span>siciano flam(ini) divor(um) Aug(ustorum) \u003Cbr id=\"